</div>=20

<h3>Symmetry</h3>=20

<p style=3D"float:left; margin: 0 10px 5px 0;"><img src=3D"https://www.math=
sisfun.com/images/style/yin-yang.svg" alt=3D"yin yang" height=3D"120" width=
=3D"120"></p>   =20
<p>Binary numbers also have a beautiful and elegant pattern:</p>=20
<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/numbers/images/b=
inary-symmetry.svg" alt=3D"binary symmetry" height=3D"180" width=3D"93"></p=
> =20
<div style=3D"clear:both"></div><br>

<p>Here are some larger  values:</p>=20
<div class=3D"simple">

	<table style=3D"border: 0; margin:auto;">
		<tbody><tr style=3D"text-align:center;">
			<th scope=3D"col">Decimal:</th>
			<td>20</td>
			<td>25</td>
			<td>30</td>
			<td>40</td>
			<td>50</td>
			<td>100</td>
			<td>200</td>
			<td>500</td>
		</tr>
		<tr style=3D"text-align:center;">
			<th scope=3D"col">Binary:</th>
			<td>10100</td>
			<td>11001</td>
			<td>11110</td>
			<td>101000</td>
			<td>110010</td>
			<td>1100100</td>
			<td>11001000</td>
			<td>111110100</td>
		</tr>
	</tbody></table>=20
</div>=20

<p class=3D"center large">"Binary is as easy as 1, 10, 11."</p>=20
<p>Now see how to use binary to count past 1.000 on your fingers:</p>=20
<div class=3D"activity"><a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/numbers/binar=
y-count-fingers.html">Activity: Binary Fingers</a>
</div>=20

<p>&nbsp;</p>=20


<h2>Position</h2>=20

<p>In the <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/decimals.html">Decimal Syst=
em</a> there are  Ones, Tens, Hundreds, etc</p>=20
<p>In <b>binary</b> there are Ones, Twos, Fours, etc, like this:</p>=20
<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/numbers/images/b=
inary-number.svg" alt=3D"binary number 1101.101" height=3D"184" width=3D"48=
9"></p>=20
<p class=3D"center large">This is  1=C3=978 + 1=C3=974 + 0=C3=972 + 1 + 1=
=C3=97(1/2) + 0=C3=97(1/4) + 1=C3=97(1/8)<br>
=3D <b>13,625 in Decimal</b></p>=20
<p>&nbsp;</p>=20
<p>Numbers can be placed to the left or right of the point, to show values =
greater than one and less than one.</p>

	<table class=3D"center">
		<tbody><tr>
			<td colspan=3D"2" class=3D"huge">10,1</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td style=3D"width:105px;"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/images=
/style/left.svg" alt=3D"left arrow" height=3D"49" width=3D"50"><img src=3D"=
https://www.mathsisfun.com/images/style/dot-blue.svg" alt=3D"dot blue" heig=
ht=3D"12" width=3D"12"></td>
			<td>The number to the left of the  point is a whole number (in this exam=
ple 10)</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td class=3D"larger">&nbsp;</td>
			<td class=3D"larger">&nbsp;</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td colspan=3D"2" class=3D"large">As we move further left, every number =
place gets <b>2 times bigger</b>.</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td class=3D"larger">&nbsp;</td>
			<td class=3D"larger">&nbsp;</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td style=3D"text-align: right;"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/=
images/style/dot-blue.svg" alt=3D"dot blue" height=3D"12" width=3D"12"><img=
 src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/images/style/right.svg" alt=3D"right arr=
ow" height=3D"49" width=3D"50"></td>
			<td class=3D"">The first digit on the right means <b> halves</b> (1/2)</=
td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td class=3D"larger">&nbsp;</td>
			<td class=3D"larger">&nbsp;</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td class=3D"larger">&nbsp;</td>
			<td class=3D"large" style=3D"text-align: right;">As we move further righ=
t, every number place gets <b>2 times smaller</b> (half as big)</td>
		</tr>
	</tbody></table>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Example: 10,1</h3>=20

	<ul>=20
		<li>The "10" means 2 in decimal,</li>=20
		<li>The ".1" means half,</li>=20
		<li>So "10,1" in binary is 2,5 in decimal</li>=20
	</ul>=20
	</div>
<p>You can do conversions at <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/binary-d=
ecimal-hexadecimal-converter.html">Binary to Decimal to Hexadecimal Convert=
er</a>.</p>=20


<h2>Words</h2>=20

<div class=3D"words">=20
<p>The word <b>binary</b> comes from "Bi-" meaning two. We see "bi-"  in wo=
rds such as "bicycle" (two wheels) or "binocular" (two eyes).</p>=20
</div>
<div class=3D"words">=20
<p>A single binary digit (like "0" or "1") is called a "bit".</p>=20
<p>For example <b>11010</b> is five bits long.</p>=20
<p>The word<b> bit</b> is made up from the words "<b>b</b>inary dig<b>it</b=
>"</p>=20
</div>
<p>And:</p>
<div class=3D"words">=20
<p>When you <b>say</b> a  binary number, pronounce each digit.</p>
<p>Example: the binary number "101" is spoken as <i>"one zero one"</i>, or =
sometimes <i>"one-oh-one"</i>.</p>
<p>This way  people won't confuse it with a decimal number.</p>=20
</div>


<h2>How to Show that a Number is Binary</h2>=20

<p>To show that a number is a <i>binary</i> number, follow it with a little=
 2 like this: <b>101<sub>2</sub></b></p>=20
<p>This way people won't think it is the decimal number "101" (one hundred =
and one).</p>=20


<h2>Examples</h2>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Example: What is 1111<b><sub>2</sub></b> in Decimal?</h3>=20

	<ul>=20
		<li>The "1" on the left is in the "2=C3=972=C3=972" position, so that mea=
ns  1=C3=972=C3=972=C3=972 (=3D8)</li>=20
		<li>The next "1"  is in the "2=C3=972" position, so that means  1=C3=972=
=C3=972 (=3D4)</li>=20
		<li>The next "1"  is in the "2" position, so that means  1=C3=972 (=3D2)<=
/li>=20
		<li>The last "1"  is in the ones position, so that means  1</li>=20
		<li>Answer: 1111 =3D 8+4+2+1  =3D 15 in Decimal</li>=20
	</ul>=20
	</div>

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Example: What is 1001<b><sub>2</sub></b> in Decimal?</h3>=20

	<ul>=20
		<li>The "1" on the left is in the "2=C3=972=C3=972" position, so that mea=
ns  1=C3=972=C3=972=C3=972 (=3D8)</li>=20
		<li>The "0"  is in the "2=C3=972" position, so that means  0=C3=972=C3=97=
2 (=3D0)</li>=20
		<li>The next "0"  is in the "2" position, so that means  0=C3=972 (=3D0)<=
/li>=20
		<li>The last "1"  is in the ones position, so that means  1</li>=20
		<li>Answer: 1001 =3D 8+0+0+1 =3D 9 in Decimal</li>=20
	</ul>=20
	</div>

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Example: What is 1,1<b><sub>2</sub></b> in Decimal?</h3>=20

	<ul>=20
		<li>The "1" on the left side is in the ones position, so that means 1.</l=
i>=20
		<li>The 1 on the right side is in the "halves" position, so that means 1=
=C3=97(1/2)</li>=20
		<li>So, 1,1 is "1 and 1 half" =3D 1,5 in Decimal</li>=20
	</ul>=20
	</div>

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Example: What is 10,11<b><sub>2</sub></b> in Decimal?</h3>=20

	<ul>=20
		<li>The "1" is in the "2" position, so that means  1=C3=972 (=3D2)</li>=
=20
		<li>The "0"  is in the ones position, so that means  0</li>=20
		<li>The "1" on the right of the point  is in the "halves" position, so th=
at means 1=C3=97(1/2)</li>=20
		<li>The last "1" on the right side is in the "quarters" position, so that=
 means 1=C3=97(1/4)</li>=20
		<li>So, 10,11 is 2+0+1/2+1/4 =3D 2,75 in Decimal</li>=20
	</ul>=20
	</div>
<p class=3D"center large">"There are 10 kinds of people in the world,<br>
those who understand binary numbers, and those who don't."</p>=20
